<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do you calculate startup runway?", answer: "Startup runway is calculated by dividing your current cash balance by your net monthly burn rate (monthly expenses minus monthly revenue). For example, if you have $500,000 in cash and burn $50,000 net per month, your runway is 10 months. If you have revenue growth, the calculation accounts for decreasing burn over time." },
  { question: "What is a good startup runway?", answer: "Most investors and advisors recommend maintaining at least 12-18 months of runway. This gives you enough time to hit milestones and raise your next round of funding. Less than 6 months is considered critical, as fundraising typically takes 3-6 months. More than 24 months gives you significant flexibility." },
  { question: "What is burn rate vs. net burn rate?", answer: "Gross burn rate is your total monthly expenses regardless of revenue. Net burn rate is gross burn minus monthly revenue. Net burn is the more relevant metric because it shows how fast you are actually consuming cash. A company with $100,000 in expenses and $40,000 in revenue has a net burn of $60,000." },
  { question: "When should a startup start fundraising?", answer: "Start fundraising when you have at least 6-9 months of runway remaining. The fundraising process typically takes 3-6 months from first meeting to money in the bank. Starting too late puts you in a weak negotiating position and risks running out of cash during the process." },
  { question: "How can a startup extend its runway?", answer: "Startups can extend runway by increasing revenue, reducing expenses, or raising additional capital. Specific tactics include renegotiating vendor contracts, reducing headcount costs through part-time or contractor roles, focusing on higher-margin products, cutting non-essential spending, and pursuing bridge financing or revenue-based financing." }
]) %>

